1086/285697 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = McNab | first1 = B.K. | year = 2002 | title = Minimizing energy expenditure facilitates vertebrate persistence on oceanic islands | url = | journal = Ecology Letters | volume = 5 | issue = 5| pages = 693\u2013704 | doi=10.1046/j.1461-0248.2002.00365.x}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = McNab | first1 = B.K. | last2 = Ellis | first2 = H.I. | year = 2006 | title = Flightless rails endemic to islands have lower energy expenditures and clutch sizes than flighted rails on islands and continents | url = | journal = Comparative Biochemistry and Physiology A \u2013 Molecular & Integrative Physiology | volume = 145 | issue = 3| pages = 295\u2013311 | doi = 10.1016/j.cbpa.2006.02.025 | pmid = 16632395 }}\n* Ml\u00edkovsk\u00fd, Jir\u00ed (2002): ''Cenozoic Birds of the World, Part 1: Europe''. Ninox Press, Prague. <small>{{Listed Invalid ISBN|80-901105-3-8}}</small> [http://www.nm.cz/download/JML-18-2002-CBE.pdf PDF fulltext]<!-- This should be treated with extreme caution as regards merging of species. Splits are usually good though. See also critical review in Auk121:623-627 here http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3793/is_200404/ai_n9396879 -->\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Perret | first1 = P. | last2 = Blondel | first2 = J. | year = 1993 | title = Experimental-evidence of the territorial defense hypothesis in insular blue tits | url = | journal = Experientia | volume = 49 | issue = | pages = 94\u201398 | doi=10.1007/bf01928800}}\n* [[Storrs L. Olson|Olson, Storrs L.]] (1985): Section X.D.2.b. Scolopacidae. ''In:'' Farner, D.S.; King, J.R. & Parkes, Kenneth C. (eds.): ''Avian Biology'' '''8''': 174\u2013175. Academic Press, New York.\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Slikas | first1 = B. | authorlink2 = Storrs L. Olson | last2 = Olson | first2 = Storrs L. | last3 = Fleischer | first3 = R.C. | year = 2002 | title = Rapid, independent evolution of flightlessness in four species of Pacific Island rails (Rallidae): an analysis based on mitochondrial sequence data | url = | journal = [[Journal of Avian Biology|J. Avian Biol.]] | volume = 33 | issue = 1| pages = 5\u201314 | doi = 10.1034/j.1600-048X.2002.330103.x }}\n* Steadman, David William (2006): ''Extinction and Biogeography of Tropical Pacific Birds''. University of Chicago Press. {{ISBN|0-226-77142-3}}\n* {{Cite journal|pmc=1691940|year=1997|last1=Trewick|first1=S. A.|title=Flightlessness and phylogeny amongst endemic rails (Aves:Rallidae) of the New Zealand region|journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences|volume=352|issue=1352|pages=429\u2013446|doi=10.1098/rstb.1997.0031|pmid=9163823|jstor=56680}} (Full text)\n* [[Trevor H. Worthy|Worthy, Trevor H.]]; Tennyson, A.J.D.; Jones, C.; McNamara, J.A. & Douglas, B.J. (2007): Miocene waterfowl and other birds from central Otago, New Zealand. ''[[Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|J. Syst. Palaeontol.]]'' '''5'''(1): 1\u201339. {{doi|10.1017/S1477201906001957}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Rallidae|''Rallidae''}}\n*{{Cite NSRW|wstitle=Rail|short=x}}\n\n{{Birds|state=collapsed}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q26623}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rallidae| ]]\n[[Category:Extant Eocene first appearances]]\n[[Category:Rails]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading:Journal cites:, templated 1 journal cites", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rail_(bird)"}
{"title_page": "Yannick Bollor\u00e9", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Yannick Bollor\u00e9\n| image       = Yannick Bollor\u00e9.jpg\n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1980|2|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Paris]], France\n| nationality = French\n| education   = [[Paris Dauphine University]]\n| occupation  = Chairman and CEO, [[Havas]]\n| parents     = [[Vincent Bollor\u00e9]]\n| spouse      = Chlo\u00e9 Bouygues\n}}\n\n'''Yannick Bollor\u00e9''' (born 1 February 1980) is the chairman and chief executive officer (CEO) of [[Havas]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.havas.com/group/management-committee/executive-committee|title=Executive Committee|last=|first=|date=|website=Havas.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421071939/https://www.havas.com/group/management-committee/executive-committee|archive-date=21 August 2016|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> the fifth largest global communications company, a subsidiary of [[Bollor\u00e9 Group]], the business empire of his family, chaired by his father [[Vincent Bollor\u00e9|Vincent]].\n\n==Career==\n\nHaving begun a [[Dipl\u00f4me d'\u00e9tudes approfondies|DESS]] (French university degree) in audio-visual communication, in 2002 Bollor\u00e9 founded film production company WY Productions, whose films include Hell, Des vents contraires and Amiti\u00e9s sinc\u00e8res, together with Wassim B\u00e9ji, nephew of [[French-Tunisian]] producer Tarak Ben Ammar.\n\nIn July 2006, he joined Bollor\u00e9 Group chaired by his father Vincent, as programs director of [[Direct 8]], a TV channel with the highest audience growth of any French television channel at the time. From September 2009 to September 2010, he was CEO of Bollor\u00e9 M\u00e9dia,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/profile/person/16255200|title=Yannick Bollore: Chairman/CEO, Havas SA|date=|work=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|access-date=9 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> which includes TV channel Direct 8, the freesheets Direct Matin (largest daily paper in France with over one million circulation) and Direct Soir, the Bollor\u00e9 Interm\u00e9dia advertising network, and opinion pollster CSA. In March 2010, he purchased the [[Virgin 17]] television channel from [[Lagard\u00e8re Group|Lagard\u00e8re]] and in September relaunched it under a new brand [[Direct Star]]. Between October 2009 and June 2010, he founded several companies including Havas Productions, H2O Productions and Direct Cin\u00e9ma, a joint film production company.\n\nYannick Bollor\u00e9 was appointed vice-president of Havas in March 2011. In September 2011, he signed a deal to sell the television business of Bollor\u00e9 M\u00e9dia, which had become the no. 3 private radio and TV broadcaster in France, to [[Canal+ Group]] for close to \u20ac465 million in exchange for [[Vivendi]] shares,<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/canal-buys-60-bollores-tv-233400 ''Canal Plus Buys 60% of Bollore's TV Business''], hollywoodreporter.com, 9/9/2011</ref> which makes Bollor\u00e9 Group the largest Vivendi shareholder.\n\nYannick Bollor\u00e9 has been a director of Bollor\u00e9 Participations since 1998, Bollor\u00e9 since 2009 and Havas since 2010. He has been a member of the influential club ''[[Le Si\u00e8cle (think tank)|Le Si\u00e8cle]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn June 2006, Yannick Bollor\u00e9 married Chlo\u00e9 Bouygues, niece of [[Martin Bouygues]].\n\n==Awards and honours==\n*Young Global Leader at the [[World Economic Forum]] (since 2008){{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n*[[B'nai Brith]] Gold Medal, for having \u201cillustrated and defended the individual and universal values of ethics and philosophical and religious morals\u201d (2010){{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n*[[Chevalier de l'Ordre des arts et lettres de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise]] (Knight of the Order of Arts and Letters of the French Republic) (2012){{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bollore, Yannick}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Advertising people]]\n[[Category:French people of Breton descent]]\n[[Category:French chief executives]]\n[[Category:Paris Dauphine University alumni]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]]\n\n\n{{france-business-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Yannick Bollor\u00e9\n| image       = Yannick Bollor\u00e9.jpg\n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1980|2|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Paris]], France\n| nationality = French\n| education   = [[Paris Dauphine University]]\n| occupation  = Chairman and CEO, [[Havas]]\n| parents     = [[Vincent Bollor\u00e9]]\n| spouse      = Chlo\u00e9 Bouygues\n}}\n\n'''Yannick Bollor\u00e9''' (born 1 February 1980) is the chairman and chief executive officer (CEO) of [[Havas]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.havas.com/group/management-committee/executive-committee|title=Executive Committee|last=|first=|date=|website=Havas.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421071939/https://www.havas.com/group/management-committee/executive-committee|archive-date=21 August 2016|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> the fifth largest global communications company, a subsidiary of [[Bollor\u00e9 Group]], the business empire of his family, chaired by his father [[Vincent Bollor\u00e9|Vincent]].\n\n==Career==\n\nHaving begun a [[Master of Advanced Studies#France and francophone countries|DESS]] (French university degree) in audio-visual communication, in 2002 Bollor\u00e9 founded film production company WY Productions, whose films include Hell, Des vents contraires and Amiti\u00e9s sinc\u00e8res, together with Wassim B\u00e9ji, nephew of [[French-Tunisian]] producer Tarak Ben Ammar.\n\nIn July 2006, he joined Bollor\u00e9 Group chaired by his father Vincent, as programs director of [[Direct 8]], a TV channel with the highest audience growth of any French television channel at the time. From September 2009 to September 2010, he was CEO of Bollor\u00e9 M\u00e9dia,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/profile/person/16255200|title=Yannick Bollore: Chairman/CEO, Havas SA|date=|work=[[Bloomberg]]|access-date=9 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> which includes TV channel Direct 8, the freesheets Direct Matin (largest daily paper in France with over one million circulation) and Direct Soir, the Bollor\u00e9 Interm\u00e9dia advertising network, and opinion pollster CSA. In March 2010, he purchased the [[Virgin 17]] television channel from [[Lagard\u00e8re Group|Lagard\u00e8re]] and in September relaunched it under a new brand [[Direct Star]]. Between October 2009 and June 2010, he founded several companies including Havas Productions, H2O Productions and Direct Cin\u00e9ma, a joint film production company.\n\nYannick Bollor\u00e9 was appointed vice-president of Havas in March 2011. In September 2011, he signed a deal to sell the television business of Bollor\u00e9 M\u00e9dia, which had become the no. 3 private radio and TV broadcaster in France, to [[Canal+ Group]] for close to \u20ac465 million in exchange for [[Vivendi]] shares,<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/canal-buys-60-bollores-tv-233400 ''Canal Plus Buys 60% of Bollore's TV Business''], hollywoodreporter.com, 9/9/2011</ref> which makes Bollor\u00e9 Group the largest Vivendi shareholder.\n\nYannick Bollor\u00e9 has been a director of Bollor\u00e9 Participations since 1998, Bollor\u00e9 since 2009 and Havas since 2010. He has been a member of the influential club ''[[Le Si\u00e8cle (think tank)|Le Si\u00e8cle]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn June 2006, Yannick Bollor\u00e9 married Chlo\u00e9 Bouygues, niece of [[Martin Bouygues]].\n\n==Awards and honours==\n*Young Global Leader at the [[World Economic Forum]] (since 2008){{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n*[[B'nai Brith]] Gold Medal, for having \u201cillustrated and defended the individual and universal values of ethics and philosophical and religious morals\u201d (2010){{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n*[[Chevalier de l'Ordre des arts et lettres de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise]] (Knight of the Order of Arts and Letters of the French Republic) (2012){{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bollore, Yannick}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Advertising people]]\n[[Category:French people of Breton descent]]\n[[Category:French chief executives]]\n[[Category:Paris Dauphine University alumni]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]]\n\n\n{{france-business-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Insolent1", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Bloomberg\u2192Bloomberg L.P.usingDab solver", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yannick_Bollor%C3%A9"}
{"title_page": "Oseltamivir total synthesis", "text_new": "[[File:Oseltamivir-3D-balls.png|thumb|right|Oseltamivir]]'''Oseltamivir total synthesis''' concerns the [[total synthesis]] of the antiinfluenza drug [[oseltamivir]] <ref>''Classics in Total Synthesis III: Further Targets, Strategies, Methods'' K. C. Nicolaou, Jason S. Chen {{ISBN|978-3-527-32957-1}} 2011</ref> marketed by [[Hoffmann-La Roche]] under the [[trade name]] ''Tamiflu''. Its commercial production starts from the [[biomolecule]] [[shikimic acid]] harvested from Chinese [[star anise]]  with a limited worldwide supply. Due to its limited supply, searches for alternative synthetic routes preferably not requiring shikimic acid are underway and to date several such routes have been published. Control of stereochemistry is important: the molecule has three [[stereocenter]]s and the sought-after isomer is only 1 of 8 stereoisomers.\n\n==Commercial production==\nThe current production method is based on the first scalable synthesis developed by [[Gilead Sciences]] <ref>{{cite journal |author1=Rohloff John C. |author2=Kent Kenneth M. |author3=Postich Michael J. |author4=Becker Mark W. |author5=Chapman Harlan H. |author6=Kelly Daphne E. |author7=Lew Willard |author8=Louie Michael S. |author9=McGee Lawrence R. | year = 1998 | title = Practical Total Synthesis of the Anti-Influenza Drug GS-4104 | url = | journal = [[J. Org. Chem.]] | volume = 63 | issue = 13| pages = 4545\u20134550 | doi = 10.1021/jo980330q |display-authors=etal}}</ref> starting from naturally occurring [[quinic acid]] or [[shikimic acid]].  Due to lower yields and the extra steps required (because of the additional dehydration), the quinic acid route was dropped in favour of the one based on shikimic acid, which received further improvements by [[Hoffmann-La Roche]].<ref name=\"Laborda 1513\">{{Cite journal|last=Laborda|first=Pedro|last2=Wang|first2=Su-Yan|last3=Voglmeir|first3=Josef|date=2016-11-11|title=Influenza Neuraminidase Inhibitors: Synthetic Approaches, Derivatives and Biological Activity|journal=Molecules|language=en|volume=21|issue=11|pages=1513|doi=10.3390/molecules21111513|pmid=27845731|pmc=6274581}}</ref><ref name=\"Hayashi 4212\u20134215\">{{Cite journal|last=Hayashi|first=Yujiro|last2=Gotoh|first2=Hiroaki|last3=Hayashi|first3=Takaaki|last4=Shoji|first4=Mitsuru|date=2005-07-04|title=Diphenylprolinol Silyl Ethers as Efficient Organocatalysts for the Asymmetric Michael Reaction of Aldehydes and Nitroalkenes|journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition|language=en|volume=44|issue=27|pages=4212\u20134215|doi=10.1002/anie.200500599|pmid=15929151|issn=1521-3773}}</ref>\nThe current industrial synthesis is summarised below:\n\n[[File:Oseltamivir-industrial.png|thumb|400px|center]]\n\n==Karpf / Trussardi synthesis==\nThe current production method includes two reaction steps with potentially hazardous [[azide]]s. A reported azide-free Roche synthesis of tamiflu is summarised graphically below:<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 11300898 | volume=66 | title=New, azide-free transformation of epoxides into 1,2-diamino compounds: synthesis of the anti-influenza neuraminidase inhibitor oseltamivir phosphate (Tamiflu) | date=March 2001 | journal=J. Org. Chem. | pages=2044\u201351 | last1 = Karpf | first1 = M | last2 = Trussardi | first2 = R | doi=10.1021/jo005702l}}.</ref>\n\n[[Image:Oseltamivir azide-free synthesis.svg|thumb|center|400px|Synthesis of Tamiflu]]\n\nThe synthesis commences from naturally available (\u2212)-[[shikimic acid]].  The 3,4-pentylidene acetal [[mesylate]] is prepared in three steps: [[esterification]] with [[ethanol]] and [[thionyl chloride]]; [[ketal]]ization with [[P-Toluenesulfonic acid|''p''-toluenesulfonic acid]] and [[3-pentanone]]; and mesylation with [[triethylamine]] and [[methanesulfonyl chloride]].  Reductive opening of the [[ketal]] under modified Hunter conditions<ref>{{cite journal | journal = [[J. Org. Chem.]] | year = 1993 | volume = 58 | pages = 6756\u20136765 | doi = 10.1021/jo00076a041 | title = A selectivity study of activated ketal reduction with borane dimethyl sulfide |author1=Birgit Bartels |author2=Roger Hunter | issue = 24}}</ref> in [[dichloromethane]] yields an inseparable mixture of [[isomer]]ic mesylates.  The corresponding [[epoxide]] is formed under basic conditions with [[potassium bicarbonate]].  Using the inexpensive [[Lewis acid]] magnesium bromide diethyl etherate (commonly prepared fresh by the addition of [[magnesium]]\nturnings to [[1,2-Dibromoethane|1,2-dibromoethane]] in [[benzene]]:[[diethyl ether]]), the epoxide is opened with [[allyl amine]] to yield the corresponding 1,2-amino alcohol.  The water-immiscible [[solvent]]s [[methyl tert-butyl ether]] and [[acetonitrile]] are used to simplify the workup procedure, which involved stirring with 1&nbsp;M aqueous [[ammonium sulfate]].  Reduction on [[palladium]], promoted by [[ethanolamine]], followed by acidic workup yielded the deprotected 1,2-aminoalcohol.  The aminoalcohol was converted directly to the corresponding allyl-diamine in an interesting cascade sequence that commences with the unselective [[imination]] of [[benzaldehyde]] with [[azeotropic]] water removal in methyl tert-butyl ether.  Mesylation, followed by removal of the solid byproduct [[triethylamine]] [[hydrochloride]], results in an intermediate that was poised to undergo [[aziridination]] upon [[transimination]] with another equivalent of allylamine.  With the librated [[methanesulfonic acid]], the\n[[aziridine]] opens cleanly to yield a diamine that immediately undergoes a second transimination.  Acidic [[hydrolysis]] then removed the [[imine]].  Selective [[acylation]] with [[acetic anhydride]] (under [[buffer solution|buffered]] conditions, the 5-amino group is [[Protonation|protonated]] owing to a considerable difference in [[acid dissociation constant|p''K''<sub>a</sub>]], 4.2 vs 7.9, preventing [[acetylation]]) yields the desired ''N''-acetylated product in crystalline form upon extractive workup.  Finally, [[deallylation]] as above, yielded the [[Freebase (chemistry)|freebase]] of oseltamivir, which was converted to the desired oseltamivir phosphate by treatment with [[phosphoric acid]].  The final product is obtained in high purity (99.7%) and an overall yield of 17-22% from (\u2212)-shikimic acid.  It is noted that the synthesis avoids the use of potentially explosive [[azide]] reagents and intermediates; however, the synthesis actually used by Roche uses azides.  Roche has other routes to\noseltamivir that do not involve the use of (\u2212)-shikimic acid as a chiral pool starting material, such as a Diels-Alder route involving furan and [[ethyl acrylate]] or an [[isophthalic acid]] route, which involves catalytic hydrogenation and enzymatic desymmetrization.\n\n==Corey synthesis==\nIn 2006 the group of [[E.J. Corey]] published a novel route bypassing shikimic acid starting from [[butadiene]] and [[acrylic acid]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Yeung | first1 = Ying-Yeung | last2 = Hong | first2 = Sungwoo | last3 = Corey | first3 = E. J. | year = 2006 | title = A Short Enantioselective Pathway for the Synthesis of the Anti-Influenza Neuramidase Inhibitor Oseltamivir from 1,3-Butadiene and Acrylic Acid | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/33fcd48ff44b65ebf1f7691be5f174f0bc1f2143| journal = [[J. Am. Chem. Soc.]] | volume = 128 | issue = 19| pages = 6310\u20136311 | doi = 10.1021/ja0616433 | pmid = 16683783 }}</ref> The inventors chose not to [[patent]] this procedure which is described below.\n[[File:Corey oseltamivir synthesis.svg|center|thumb|400px|Corey 2006 oseltamivir synthesis]]\n\n[[Butadiene]] '''1''' reacts in an [[asymmetric synthesis|asymmetric]] [[Diels-Alder reaction]] with the [[esterification]] product of [[acrylic acid]] and [[2,2,2-trifluoroethanol]] '''2''' catalysed by the [[CBS catalyst]]. The [[ester]] '''3''' is converted into an [[amide]] in '''4''' by reaction with [[ammonia]] and the next step to [[lactam]] '''5''' is an [[iodolactamization]] with [[iodine]] initiated by [[trimethylsilyltriflate]]. The amide group is fitted with a [[tert-butyloxycarbonyl protecting group|BOC protecting group]] by reaction with [[Boc anhydride]] in '''6''' and the iodine substituent is removed in an  [[elimination reaction]] with [[DBU (chemistry)|DBU]] to the [[alkene]] '''7'''. Bromine is introduced in '''8''' by an allylic bromination with [[N-Bromosuccinimide|NBS]] and the amide group is cleaved with [[ethanol]] and [[caesium carbonate]] accompanied by elimination of bromide to the diene ethyl ester '''9'''. The newly formed double bond is functionalized with [[acetamide|''N''-bromoacetamide]] '''10''' catalyzed with\n[[tin(IV) bromide]] with complete control of [[stereochemistry]]. In the next step the bromine atom in '''11''' is [[nucleophilic displacement|displaced]] by the nitrogen atom in the amide group with the strong base [[Sodium bis(trimethylsilyl)amide|KHMDS]] to the [[aziridine]] '''12''' which in turn is opened by reaction with 3-pentanol '''13''' to the [[ether]] '''14'''. In the final step the BOC group is removed with [[phosphoric acid]] and the oseltamivir phosphate '''15''' is formed.\n\n==Shibasaki synthesis==\nAlso in 2006 the group of Masakatsu Shibasaki of the [[University of Tokyo]] published a synthesis again bypassing shikimic acid.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1021/ja061696k | volume=128 | title=De Novo Synthesis of Tamiflu via a Catalytic Asymmetric Ring-Opening of meso -Aziridines with TMSN 3 | year=2006 | journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society | pages=6312\u20136313 | last1 = Fukuta | first1 = Yuhei}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1021/ol062663c | volume=9 | title=Second Generation Catalytic Asymmetric Synthesis of Tamiflu:\u00a0 Allylic Substitution Route | year=2007 | journal=Organic Letters | pages=259\u2013262 | last1 = Mita | first1 = Tsuyoshi}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ShibasakiTamifluSynthesisPartI.png|thumb|Shibasaki Tamiflu SynthesisPart I]]\n[[File:ShibasakiTamifluSynthesisPartII.png|thumb|Shibasaki Tamiflu SynthesisPart II]]\nAn improved method published in 2007 starts with the [[enantioselective]] [[desymmetrization]] of [[aziridine]] '''1''' with [[trimethylsilyl azide]] (TMSN<sub>3</sub>) and a chiral catalyst to the [[azide]] '''2'''. The [[amide]] group is protected as a BOC group with [[Boc anhydride]] and [[4-Dimethylaminopyridine|DMAP]] in '''3''' and [[iodolactamization]] with [[iodine]] and [[potassium carbonate]] first gives the unstable intermediate '''4''' and then stable cyclic [[carbamate]] '''5''' after [[elimination reaction|elimination]] of [[hydrogen iodide]] with [[DBU (chemistry)|DBU]].\n\nThe amide group is reprotected as BOC '''6''' and the azide group converted to the amide '''7''' by reductive acylation with [[thioacetic acid]] and [[2,6-lutidine]]. [[Caesium carbonate]] accomplishes the [[hydrolysis]] of the carbamate group to the [[alcohol]] '''8''' which is subsequently oxidized to [[ketone]] '''9''' with [[Dess-Martin periodinane]]. Cyanophosphorylation with [[diethyl phosphorocyanidate]] (DEPC) modifies the ketone group to the cyanophosphate '''10''' paving the way for an [[Intramolecular reaction|intramolecular]] [[allylic rearrangement]] to unstable \u03b2-allyl [[organophosphate|phosphate]] '''11''' (toluene, sealed tube) which is hydrolyzed to alcohol '''12''' with [[ammonium chloride]]. This hydroxyl group has the wrong stereochemistry and is therefore [[inversion of configuration|inverted]] in a [[Mitsunobu reaction]] with [[p-nitrobenzoic acid]] followed by hydrolysis of the p-nitrobenzoate to '''13'''.\n\nA second Mitsunobu reaction then forms the [[aziridine]] '''14''' available for ring-opening reaction with [[3-Pentanol|3-pentanol]] catalyzed by [[boron trifluoride]] to ether '''15'''. In the final step the BOC group is removed (HCl) and [[phosphoric acid]] added to objective '''16'''.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Fukuyama synthesis==\nAn approach published in 2007 <ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1002/anie.200701754 | volume=46 | title=A Practical Synthesis of (\u2212)-Oseltamivir | year=2007 | journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition | pages=5734\u20135736 | last1 = Satoh | first1 = Nobuhiro}}</ref> like Corey's starts by an [[asymmetric Diels-Alder reaction]] this time with starting materials [[pyridine]] and [[acrolein]].\n\n[[File:OseltamivirFukuyamaPartI.png|thumb|Fukuyama Tamiflu SynthesisPart I]]\n[[File:OseltamivirFukuyamaPartII.png|thumb|Fukuyama Tamiflu SynthesisPart II]]\nPyridine ('''1''') is [[organic reduction|reduced]] with [[sodium borohydride]] in presence of [[benzyl chloroformate]] to the [[Carboxybenzyl|Cbz]] [[protective group|protected]] [[dihydropyridine]] '''2'''. The asymmetric Diels-Alder reaction with [[acrolein]] '''3''' is carried out with the [[McMillan catalyst]] to the [[aldehyde]] '''4''' as the [[endo isomer]] which is oxidized to the [[carboxylic acid]] '''5''' with [[sodium chlorite]], [[monopotassium phosphate]] and [[2-Methyl-2-butene|2-methyl-2-butene]]. Addition of [[bromine]] gives [[halolactonization]] product '''6''' and after replacement of the Cbz protective group by a [[Di-tert-butyl dicarbonate|BOC]] protective group in '''7''' ([[hydrogenolysis]] in the presence of [[di-tert-butyl dicarbonate|di-''tert''-butyl dicarbonate]]) a [[carbonyl]] group is introduced in intermediate '''8'''  by catalytic [[ruthenium(IV) oxide]] and [[sacrificial catalyst]] [[sodium periodate]]. Addition of [[ammonia]] cleaves the ester group to form [[amide]] '''9''' the [[alcohol]] group of which is [[mesyl]]ated to compound '''10'''.  In the next step [[iodobenzene diacetate]] is added, converting the amide in a [[Hofmann rearrangement]] to the allyl [[carbamate]] '''12''' after capturing the intermediate isocyanate with [[allyl alcohol]] '''11'''. On addition of [[sodium ethoxide]] in ethanol three reactions take place simultaneously: cleavage of the [[amide]] to form new an ethyl [[ester]] group, displacement of the mesyl group by newly formed BOC protected [[amine]] to an [[aziridine]] group and an [[elimination reaction]] forming the [[alkene]] group in '''13''' with liberation of HBr. In the final two steps the aziridine ring is opened by [[3-Pentanol|3-pentanol]] '''14''' and [[boron trifluoride]] to aminoether '''15''' with the BOC group replaced by an [[acyl]] group and on removal of the other amine protecting group ([[palladium on carbon|Pd/C]], [[triphenylphosphine|Ph<sub>3</sub>P]], and [[barbituric acid|1,3-dimethylbarbituric acid]] in ethanol) and addition of [[phosphoric acid]] oseltamivir '''16''' is obtained.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Trost synthesis==\n[[File:Trost oseltamivir synthesis.svg|thumb|Trost oseltamivir synthesis]]\nIn 2008 the group of [[Barry M. Trost]] of [[Stanford University]] published the shortest synthetic route to date.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1002/anie.200800282 | volume=47 | title=A Concise Synthesis of (\u2212)-Oseltamivir | year=2008 | journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition | pages=3759\u20133761 | last1 = Trost | first1 = Barry M.}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Hayashi Synthesis ==\nIn 2009, Hayashi et al. successfully produced an efficient, low cost synthetic route to prepare (-)-oseltamivir ('''1'''). Their goal was to design a procedure that would be suitable for large-scale production. Keeping cost, yield, and number of synthetic steps in mind, an [[Enantiomer|enantioselective]] [[total synthesis]] of ('''1''') was accomplished through three one-pot operations.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Ishikawa|first=Hayato|last2=Suzuki|first2=Takaki|last3=Hayashi|first3=Yujiro|date=2009-02-02|title=High-Yielding Synthesis of the Anti-Influenza Neuramidase Inhibitor (\u2212)-Oseltamivir by Three \"One-Pot\" Operations|journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition|language=en|volume=48|issue=7|pages=1304\u20131307|doi=10.1002/anie.200804883|pmid=19123206|issn=1521-3773}}</ref><ref name=\"Laborda 1513\"/> Hayashi et al.'s use of one-pot operations allowed them to perform several reactions steps in a single pot, which ultimately minimized the number of purification steps needed, waste, and saved time.\n[[File:1st_one-pot_operation_of_Hayashi_2009_Synthesis.png|center|thumb|400px]]\nIn the first [[One-pot synthesis|one-pot operation]], Hayashi et al. begins by using diphenylprolinol silyl ether ('''4''')<ref name=\"Hayashi 4212\u20134215\"/> as an [[Organocatalysis|organocatalyst]], along with alkoxyaldehyde ('''2''') and [[nitroalkene]] ('''3''') to perform an asymmetric [[Michael reaction]], affording an enantioselective Michael [[adduct]]. Upon addition of a diethyl vinylphosphate derivative ('''5''') to the Michael [[adduct]], a domino [[Michael reaction]] and [[Horner\u2013Wadsworth\u2013Emmons reaction|Horner-Wadsworth-Emmons]] reaction occurs due to the phosphonate group produced from ('''5''') to give an ethyl cyclohexenecarboxylate derivative along with two unwanted by-products. To transform the undesired by-products into the desired ethyl cyclohexencarboxylate derivative, the mixture of the product and by-products was treated with Cs<sub>2</sub>CO<sub>3</sub> in ethanol.  This induced a retro-Michael reaction on one by-product and a retro-[[aldol reaction]] accompanied with a Horner-Wadsworth-Emmons reaction for the other. Both by-products were successfully converted to the desired derivative. Finally, the addition of ''p''-toluenethiol with Cs<sub>2</sub>CO<sub>3</sub> gives ('''6''') in a 70% yield after being purified by [[column chromatography]], with the desired isomer dominating.<ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:2nd_one-pot_operation_Hayashi_2009_Synthesis.png|center|thumb|400px]]\nIn the second [[One-pot synthesis|one-pot operation]], [[trifluoroacetic acid]] is employed first to deprotect the ''tert''-butyl ester of ('''6'''); any excess reagent was removed via evaporation. The carboxylic acid produced as a result of the deprotection was then converted to an acyl chloride by [[oxalyl chloride]] and a catalytic amount of [[Dimethylformamide|DMF]]. Finally, addition of sodium azide, in the last reaction of the second one-pot operation, produce the acyl azide ('''7''') without any purification needed.<ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:Third_one-pot_operation_Hayashi_2009_Synthesis.png|center|thumb|400px]]\nThe final [[One-pot synthesis|one-pot operation]] begins with a [[Curtius rearrangement|Curtius Rearrangement]] of acyl azide ('''7''') to produce an isocyanate functional group at room temperature. The [[isocyanate]] derivative then reacts with [[acetic acid]] to yield the desired acetylamino moiety found in ('''1'''). This domino Curtius rearrangement and amide formation occurs in the absence of heat, which is extremely beneficial for reducing any possible hazard. The nitro moiety of ('''7''') is reduced to the desired amine observed in ('''1''') with Zn/HCl. Due to the harsh conditions of the nitro reduction, ammonia was used to neutralize the reaction. [[Potassium carbonate]] was then added to give ('''1'''), via a retro-Michael reaction of the [[thiol]]. ('''1''') was then purified by an acid/base extraction. The overall yield for the total synthesis of (-)-oseltamivir is 57%.<ref name=\":0\" /> Hayashi et al. use of inexpensive, non-hazardous reagents has allowed for an efficient, high yielding synthetic route that can allow for vast amount of novel derivatives to be produced in hopes of combatting against viruses resistant to (-)-oseltamivir.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.synarchive.com/molecule/oseltamivir Oseltamivir Total Syntheses @ SynArchive.com]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oseltamivir Total Synthesis}}\n[[Category:Total synthesis]]\n[[Category:Neuraminidase inhibitors]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Oseltamivir-3D-balls.png|thumb|right|Oseltamivir]]'''Oseltamivir total synthesis''' concerns the [[total synthesis]] of the antiinfluenza drug [[oseltamivir]] <ref>''Classics in Total Synthesis III: Further Targets, Strategies, Methods'' K. C. Nicolaou, Jason S. Chen {{ISBN|978-3-527-32957-1}} 2011</ref> marketed by [[Hoffmann-La Roche]] under the [[trade name]] ''Tamiflu''. Its commercial production starts from the [[biomolecule]] [[shikimic acid]] harvested from Chinese [[star anise]]  with a limited worldwide supply. Due to its limited supply, searches for alternative synthetic routes preferably not requiring shikimic acid are underway and to date several such routes have been published. Control of stereochemistry is important: the molecule has three [[stereocenter]]s and the sought-after isomer is only 1 of 8 stereoisomers.\n\n==Commercial production==\nThe current production method is based on the first scalable synthesis developed by [[Gilead Sciences]] <ref>{{cite journal |author1=Rohloff John C. |author2=Kent Kenneth M. |author3=Postich Michael J. |author4=Becker Mark W. |author5=Chapman Harlan H. |author6=Kelly Daphne E. |author7=Lew Willard |author8=Louie Michael S. |author9=McGee Lawrence R. | year = 1998 | title = Practical Total Synthesis of the Anti-Influenza Drug GS-4104 | url = | journal = [[J. Org. Chem.]] | volume = 63 | issue = 13| pages = 4545\u20134550 | doi = 10.1021/jo980330q |display-authors=etal}}</ref> starting from naturally occurring [[quinic acid]] or [[shikimic acid]].  Due to lower yields and the extra steps required (because of the additional dehydration), the quinic acid route was dropped in favour of the one based on shikimic acid, which received further improvements by [[Hoffmann-La Roche]].<ref name=\"Laborda 1513\">{{Cite journal|last=Laborda|first=Pedro|last2=Wang|first2=Su-Yan|last3=Voglmeir|first3=Josef|date=2016-11-11|title=Influenza Neuraminidase Inhibitors: Synthetic Approaches, Derivatives and Biological Activity|journal=Molecules|language=en|volume=21|issue=11|pages=1513|doi=10.3390/molecules21111513|pmid=27845731|pmc=6274581}}</ref><ref name=\"Hayashi 4212\u20134215\">{{Cite journal|last=Hayashi|first=Yujiro|last2=Gotoh|first2=Hiroaki|last3=Hayashi|first3=Takaaki|last4=Shoji|first4=Mitsuru|date=2005-07-04|title=Diphenylprolinol Silyl Ethers as Efficient Organocatalysts for the Asymmetric Michael Reaction of Aldehydes and Nitroalkenes|journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition|language=en|volume=44|issue=27|pages=4212\u20134215|doi=10.1002/anie.200500599|pmid=15929151|issn=1521-3773}}</ref>\nThe current industrial synthesis is summarised below:\n\n[[File:Oseltamivir-industrial.png|thumb|400px|center]]\n\n==Karpf / Trussardi synthesis==\nThe current production method includes two reaction steps with potentially hazardous [[azide]]s. A reported azide-free Roche synthesis of tamiflu is summarised graphically below:<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 11300898 | volume=66 | title=New, azide-free transformation of epoxides into 1,2-diamino compounds: synthesis of the anti-influenza neuraminidase inhibitor oseltamivir phosphate (Tamiflu) | date=March 2001 | journal=J. Org. Chem. | pages=2044\u201351 | last1 = Karpf | first1 = M | last2 = Trussardi | first2 = R | doi=10.1021/jo005702l}}.</ref>\n\n[[Image:Oseltamivir azide-free synthesis.svg|thumb|center|400px|Synthesis of Tamiflu]]\n\nThe synthesis commences from naturally available (\u2212)-[[shikimic acid]].  The 3,4-pentylidene acetal [[mesylate]] is prepared in three steps: [[esterification]] with [[ethanol]] and [[thionyl chloride]]; [[ketal]]ization with [[P-Toluenesulfonic acid|''p''-toluenesulfonic acid]] and [[3-pentanone]]; and mesylation with [[triethylamine]] and [[methanesulfonyl chloride]].  Reductive opening of the [[ketal]] under modified Hunter conditions<ref>{{cite journal | journal = [[J. Org. Chem.]] | year = 1993 | volume = 58 | pages = 6756\u20136765 | doi = 10.1021/jo00076a041 | title = A selectivity study of activated ketal reduction with borane dimethyl sulfide |author1=Birgit Bartels |author2=Roger Hunter | issue = 24}}</ref> in [[dichloromethane]] yields an inseparable mixture of [[isomer]]ic mesylates.  The corresponding [[epoxide]] is formed under basic conditions with [[potassium bicarbonate]].  Using the inexpensive [[Lewis acid]] magnesium bromide diethyl etherate (commonly prepared fresh by the addition of [[magnesium]]\nturnings to [[1,2-Dibromoethane|1,2-dibromoethane]] in [[benzene]]:[[diethyl ether]]), the epoxide is opened with [[allyl amine]] to yield the corresponding 1,2-amino alcohol.  The water-immiscible [[solvent]]s [[methyl tert-butyl ether]] and [[acetonitrile]] are used to simplify the workup procedure, which involved stirring with 1&nbsp;M aqueous [[ammonium sulfate]].  Reduction on [[palladium]], promoted by [[ethanolamine]], followed by acidic workup yielded the deprotected 1,2-aminoalcohol.  The aminoalcohol was converted directly to the corresponding allyl-diamine in an interesting cascade sequence that commences with the unselective [[imination]] of [[benzaldehyde]] with [[azeotropic]] water removal in methyl tert-butyl ether.  Mesylation, followed by removal of the solid byproduct [[triethylamine]] [[hydrochloride]], results in an intermediate that was poised to undergo [[aziridination]] upon [[transimination]] with another equivalent of allylamine.  With the librated [[methanesulfonic acid]], the\n[[aziridine]] opens cleanly to yield a diamine that immediately undergoes a second transimination.  Acidic [[hydrolysis]] then removed the [[imine]].  Selective [[acylation]] with [[acetic anhydride]] (under [[buffer solution|buffered]] conditions, the 5-amino group is [[Protonation|protonated]] owing to a considerable difference in [[acid dissociation constant|p''K''<sub>a</sub>]], 4.2 vs 7.9, preventing [[acetylation]]) yields the desired ''N''-acetylated product in crystalline form upon extractive workup.  Finally, [[deallylation]] as above, yielded the [[Freebase (chemistry)|freebase]] of oseltamivir, which was converted to the desired oseltamivir phosphate by treatment with [[phosphoric acid]].  The final product is obtained in high purity (99.7%) and an overall yield of 17-22% from (\u2212)-shikimic acid.  It is noted that the synthesis avoids the use of potentially explosive [[azide]] reagents and intermediates; however, the synthesis actually used by Roche uses azides.  Roche has other routes to\noseltamivir that do not involve the use of (\u2212)-shikimic acid as a chiral pool starting material, such as a Diels-Alder route involving furan and [[ethyl acrylate]] or an [[isophthalic acid]] route, which involves catalytic hydrogenation and enzymatic desymmetrization.\n\n==Corey synthesis==\nIn 2006 the group of [[E.J. Corey]] published a novel route bypassing shikimic acid starting from [[butadiene]] and [[acrylic acid]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Yeung | first1 = Ying-Yeung | last2 = Hong | first2 = Sungwoo | last3 = Corey | first3 = E. J. | year = 2006 | title = A Short Enantioselective Pathway for the Synthesis of the Anti-Influenza Neuramidase Inhibitor Oseltamivir from 1,3-Butadiene and Acrylic Acid | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/33fcd48ff44b65ebf1f7691be5f174f0bc1f2143| journal = [[J. Am. Chem. Soc.]] | volume = 128 | issue = 19| pages = 6310\u20136311 | doi = 10.1021/ja0616433 | pmid = 16683783 }}</ref> The inventors chose not to [[patent]] this procedure which is described below.\n[[File:Corey oseltamivir synthesis.svg|center|thumb|400px|Corey 2006 oseltamivir synthesis]]\n\n[[Butadiene]] '''1''' reacts in an [[asymmetric synthesis|asymmetric]] [[Diels-Alder reaction]] with the [[esterification]] product of [[acrylic acid]] and [[2,2,2-trifluoroethanol]] '''2''' catalysed by the [[CBS catalyst]]. The [[ester]] '''3''' is converted into an [[amide]] in '''4''' by reaction with [[ammonia]] and the next step to [[lactam]] '''5''' is an [[iodolactamization]] with [[iodine]] initiated by [[trimethylsilyltriflate]]. The amide group is fitted with a [[tert-butyloxycarbonyl protecting group|BOC protecting group]] by reaction with [[Boc anhydride]] in '''6''' and the iodine substituent is removed in an  [[elimination reaction]] with [[DBU (chemistry)|DBU]] to the [[alkene]] '''7'''. Bromine is introduced in '''8''' by an allylic bromination with [[N-Bromosuccinimide|NBS]] and the amide group is cleaved with [[ethanol]] and [[caesium carbonate]] accompanied by elimination of bromide to the diene ethyl ester '''9'''. The newly formed double bond is functionalized with [[acetamide|''N''-bromoacetamide]] '''10''' catalyzed with\n[[tin(IV) bromide]] with complete control of [[stereochemistry]]. In the next step the bromine atom in '''11''' is [[nucleophilic displacement|displaced]] by the nitrogen atom in the amide group with the strong base [[Sodium bis(trimethylsilyl)amide|KHMDS]] to the [[aziridine]] '''12''' which in turn is opened by reaction with 3-pentanol '''13''' to the [[ether]] '''14'''. In the final step the BOC group is removed with [[phosphoric acid]] and the oseltamivir phosphate '''15''' is formed.\n\n==Shibasaki synthesis==\nAlso in 2006 the group of Masakatsu Shibasaki of the [[University of Tokyo]] published a synthesis again bypassing shikimic acid.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1021/ja061696k | volume=128 | title=De Novo Synthesis of Tamiflu via a Catalytic Asymmetric Ring-Opening of meso -Aziridines with TMSN 3 | year=2006 | journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society | pages=6312\u20136313 | last1 = Fukuta | first1 = Yuhei}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1021/ol062663c | volume=9 | title=Second Generation Catalytic Asymmetric Synthesis of Tamiflu:\u00a0 Allylic Substitution Route | year=2007 | journal=Organic Letters | pages=259\u2013262 | last1 = Mita | first1 = Tsuyoshi}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ShibasakiTamifluSynthesisPartI.png|thumb|Shibasaki Tamiflu SynthesisPart I]]\n[[File:ShibasakiTamifluSynthesisPartII.png|thumb|Shibasaki Tamiflu SynthesisPart II]]\nAn improved method published in 2007 starts with the [[enantioselective]] [[desymmetrization]] of [[aziridine]] '''1''' with [[trimethylsilyl azide]] (TMSN<sub>3</sub>) and a chiral catalyst to the [[azide]] '''2'''. The [[amide]] group is protected as a BOC group with [[Boc anhydride]] and [[4-Dimethylaminopyridine|DMAP]] in '''3''' and [[iodolactamization]] with [[iodine]] and [[potassium carbonate]] first gives the unstable intermediate '''4''' and then stable cyclic [[carbamate]] '''5''' after [[elimination reaction|elimination]] of [[hydrogen iodide]] with [[DBU (chemistry)|DBU]].\n\nThe amide group is reprotected as BOC '''6''' and the azide group converted to the amide '''7''' by reductive acylation with [[thioacetic acid]] and [[2,6-lutidine]]. [[Caesium carbonate]] accomplishes the [[hydrolysis]] of the carbamate group to the [[alcohol]] '''8''' which is subsequently oxidized to [[ketone]] '''9''' with [[Dess-Martin periodinane]]. Cyanophosphorylation with [[diethyl phosphorocyanidate]] (DEPC) modifies the ketone group to the cyanophosphate '''10''' paving the way for an [[Intramolecular reaction|intramolecular]] [[allylic rearrangement]] to unstable \u03b2-allyl [[organophosphate|phosphate]] '''11''' (toluene, sealed tube) which is hydrolyzed to alcohol '''12''' with [[ammonium chloride]]. This hydroxyl group has the wrong stereochemistry and is therefore [[inversion of configuration|inverted]] in a [[Mitsunobu reaction]] with [[p-nitrobenzoic acid]] followed by hydrolysis of the p-nitrobenzoate to '''13'''.\n\nA second Mitsunobu reaction then forms the [[aziridine]] '''14''' available for ring-opening reaction with [[3-Pentanol|3-pentanol]] catalyzed by [[boron trifluoride]] to ether '''15'''. In the final step the BOC group is removed (HCl) and [[phosphoric acid]] added to objective '''16'''.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Fukuyama synthesis==\nAn approach published in 2007 <ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1002/anie.200701754 | volume=46 | title=A Practical Synthesis of (\u2212)-Oseltamivir | year=2007 | journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition | pages=5734\u20135736 | last1 = Satoh | first1 = Nobuhiro}}</ref> like Corey's starts by an [[asymmetric Diels-Alder reaction]] this time with starting materials [[pyridine]] and [[acrolein]].\n\n[[File:OseltamivirFukuyamaPartI.png|thumb|Fukuyama Tamiflu SynthesisPart I]]\n[[File:OseltamivirFukuyamaPartII.png|thumb|Fukuyama Tamiflu SynthesisPart II]]\nPyridine ('''1''') is [[organic reduction|reduced]] with [[sodium borohydride]] in presence of [[benzyl chloroformate]] to the [[Carboxybenzyl|Cbz]] [[protective group|protected]] [[dihydropyridine]] '''2'''. The asymmetric Diels-Alder reaction with [[acrolein]] '''3''' is carried out with the [[McMillan catalyst]] to the [[aldehyde]] '''4''' as the [[endo isomer]] which is oxidized to the [[carboxylic acid]] '''5''' with [[sodium chlorite]], [[monopotassium phosphate]] and [[2-Methyl-2-butene|2-methyl-2-butene]]. Addition of [[bromine]] gives [[halolactonization]] product '''6''' and after replacement of the Cbz protective group by a [[Di-tert-butyl dicarbonate|BOC]] protective group in '''7''' ([[hydrogenolysis]] in the presence of [[di-tert-butyl dicarbonate|di-''tert''-butyl dicarbonate]]) a [[carbonyl]] group is introduced in intermediate '''8'''  by catalytic [[ruthenium(IV) oxide]] and [[sacrificial catalyst]] [[sodium periodate]]. Addition of [[ammonia]] cleaves the ester group to form [[amide]] '''9''' the [[alcohol]] group of which is [[mesyl]]ated to compound '''10'''.  In the next step [[iodobenzene diacetate]] is added, converting the amide in a [[Hofmann rearrangement]] to the allyl [[carbamate]] '''12''' after capturing the intermediate isocyanate with [[allyl alcohol]] '''11'''. On addition of [[sodium ethoxide]] in ethanol three reactions take place simultaneously: cleavage of the [[amide]] to form new an ethyl [[ester]] group, displacement of the mesyl group by newly formed BOC protected [[amine]] to an [[aziridine]] group and an [[elimination reaction]] forming the [[alkene]] group in '''13''' with liberation of HBr. In the final two steps the aziridine ring is opened by [[3-Pentanol|3-pentanol]] '''14''' and [[boron trifluoride]] to aminoether '''15''' with the BOC group replaced by an [[acyl]] group and on removal of the other amine protecting group ([[palladium on carbon|Pd/C]], [[triphenylphosphine|Ph<sub>3</sub>P]], and [[barbituric acid|1,3-dimethylbarbituric acid]] in ethanol) and addition of [[phosphoric acid]] oseltamivir '''16''' is obtained.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Trost synthesis==\n[[File:Trost oseltamivir synthesis.svg|thumb|Trost oseltamivir synthesis]]\nIn 2008 the group of [[Barry M. Trost]] of [[Stanford University]] published the shortest synthetic route to date.<ref>''A Concise Synthesis of (\u2212)-Oseltamivir'' Barry M.Trost, Ting Zhang [[Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.]] '''2008''', 47, 1-4 {{DOI|10.1002/anie.200800282}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Hayashi Synthesis ==\nIn 2009, Hayashi et al. successfully produced an efficient, low cost synthetic route to prepare (-)-oseltamivir ('''1'''). Their goal was to design a procedure that would be suitable for large-scale production. Keeping cost, yield, and number of synthetic steps in mind, an [[Enantiomer|enantioselective]] [[total synthesis]] of ('''1''') was accomplished through three one-pot operations.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Ishikawa|first=Hayato|last2=Suzuki|first2=Takaki|last3=Hayashi|first3=Yujiro|date=2009-02-02|title=High-Yielding Synthesis of the Anti-Influenza Neuramidase Inhibitor (\u2212)-Oseltamivir by Three \"One-Pot\" Operations|journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition|language=en|volume=48|issue=7|pages=1304\u20131307|doi=10.1002/anie.200804883|pmid=19123206|issn=1521-3773}}</ref><ref name=\"Laborda 1513\"/> Hayashi et al.'s use of one-pot operations allowed them to perform several reactions steps in a single pot, which ultimately minimized the number of purification steps needed, waste, and saved time.\n[[File:1st_one-pot_operation_of_Hayashi_2009_Synthesis.png|center|thumb|400px]]\nIn the first [[One-pot synthesis|one-pot operation]], Hayashi et al. begins by using diphenylprolinol silyl ether ('''4''')<ref name=\"Hayashi 4212\u20134215\"/> as an [[Organocatalysis|organocatalyst]], along with alkoxyaldehyde ('''2''') and [[nitroalkene]] ('''3''') to perform an asymmetric [[Michael reaction]], affording an enantioselective Michael [[adduct]]. Upon addition of a diethyl vinylphosphate derivative ('''5''') to the Michael [[adduct]], a domino [[Michael reaction]] and [[Horner\u2013Wadsworth\u2013Emmons reaction|Horner-Wadsworth-Emmons]] reaction occurs due to the phosphonate group produced from ('''5''') to give an ethyl cyclohexenecarboxylate derivative along with two unwanted by-products. To transform the undesired by-products into the desired ethyl cyclohexencarboxylate derivative, the mixture of the product and by-products was treated with Cs<sub>2</sub>CO<sub>3</sub> in ethanol.  This induced a retro-Michael reaction on one by-product and a retro-[[aldol reaction]] accompanied with a Horner-Wadsworth-Emmons reaction for the other. Both by-products were successfully converted to the desired derivative. Finally, the addition of ''p''-toluenethiol with Cs<sub>2</sub>CO<sub>3</sub> gives ('''6''') in a 70% yield after being purified by [[column chromatography]], with the desired isomer dominating.<ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:2nd_one-pot_operation_Hayashi_2009_Synthesis.png|center|thumb|400px]]\nIn the second [[One-pot synthesis|one-pot operation]], [[trifluoroacetic acid]] is employed first to deprotect the ''tert''-butyl ester of ('''6'''); any excess reagent was removed via evaporation. The carboxylic acid produced as a result of the deprotection was then converted to an acyl chloride by [[oxalyl chloride]] and a catalytic amount of [[Dimethylformamide|DMF]]. Finally, addition of sodium azide, in the last reaction of the second one-pot operation, produce the acyl azide ('''7''') without any purification needed.<ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:Third_one-pot_operation_Hayashi_2009_Synthesis.png|center|thumb|400px]]\nThe final [[One-pot synthesis|one-pot operation]] begins with a [[Curtius rearrangement|Curtius Rearrangement]] of acyl azide ('''7''') to produce an isocyanate functional group at room temperature. The [[isocyanate]] derivative then reacts with [[acetic acid]] to yield the desired acetylamino moiety found in ('''1'''). This domino Curtius rearrangement and amide formation occurs in the absence of heat, which is extremely beneficial for reducing any possible hazard. The nitro moiety of ('''7''') is reduced to the desired amine observed in ('''1''') with Zn/HCl. Due to the harsh conditions of the nitro reduction, ammonia was used to neutralize the reaction. [[Potassium carbonate]] was then added to give ('''1'''), via a retro-Michael reaction of the [[thiol]]. ('''1''') was then purified by an acid/base extraction. The overall yield for the total synthesis of (-)-oseltamivir is 57%.<ref name=\":0\" /> Hayashi et al. use of inexpensive, non-hazardous reagents has allowed for an efficient, high yielding synthetic route that can allow for vast amount of novel derivatives to be produced in hopes of combatting against viruses resistant to (-)-oseltamivir.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.synarchive.com/molecule/oseltamivir Oseltamivir Total Syntheses @ SynArchive.com]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oseltamivir Total Synthesis}}\n[[Category:Total synthesis]]\n[[Category:Neuraminidase inhibitors]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oseltamivir_total_synthesis"}
