ank        = 10th\n| population_density_km2 = 2,238\n| population_blank1_title= Census figures\n| population_blank1      = 320,262\n| population_note        = (Census count)\n| timezone               = [[UTC+07:00|ICT]]\n| utc_offset             = +7\n| timezone_DST           =\n| utc_offset_DST         =\n| postal_code_type       = [[Postal codes in Thailand|Postcode]]\n| postal_code            = 20150\n| area_code_type         = [[Telephone numbers in Thailand|Calling code]]\n| area_code              = 038\n| blank_name             = [[ISO 3166-2:TH|ISO 3166-2]]\n| blank_info             = TH-S\n| website                = {{URL|http://www.pattaya.go.th}}\n| footnotes              =\n}}\n\n'''Pattaya''' ({{lang-th|\u0e1e\u0e31\u0e17\u0e22\u0e32}}, {{RTGS|''Phatthaya''}}, {{IPA-th|p\u02b0\u00e1t.t\u02b0\u0101.j\u0101\u02d0|pron|th-pattaya.ogg}}) is a city in [[Thailand]]. It is on the east coast of the [[Gulf of Thailand]], about {{convert|100|km}} southeast of [[Bangkok]], within, but not part of, [[Bang Lamung District]] in the province of [[Chonburi Province|Chonburi]]. Pattaya City ({{lang-th|\u0e40\u0e21\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e1e\u0e31\u0e17\u0e22\u0e32}}, {{RTGS|''Mueang Phatthaya''}}) is a self-governing municipal area which covers [[tambon]]s Nong Prue and Na Klua and parts of Huai Yai and Nong Pla Lai. The city is in the industrial [[Eastern Seaboard of Thailand|Eastern Seaboard]] zone, along with [[Si Racha]], [[Laem Chabang]], and [[Chonburi (city)|Chonburi]]. Pattaya is at the center of the Pattaya-Chonburi Metropolitan Area\u2014a [[wikt:conurbation|conurbation]] in Chonburi Province\u2014with a population of roughly 1,000,000.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Pattaya,_Thailand_Skyline.jpg|thumb|left|Pattaya skyline]]\n\nThe name ''Pattaya'' evolved from the march of [[Phraya]] Tak (later [[King Taksin]]) and his army from [[Phra Nakhon Si Ayutthaya Province|Ayutthaya]] to [[Chanthaburi Province|Chanthaburi]], which took place before the fall of the former capital to [[Burma|Burmese]] invaders in 1767. When his army arrived in the vicinity of what is now Pattaya, Phraya Tak encountered the troops of a local leader named Nai Klom, who tried to intercept him. When the two met face to face, Nai Klom was impressed by Phraya Tak's dignified manner and his army's strict discipline. He surrendered without a fight and joined his forces. The place the armies confronted each other was thereafter known as \"Thap Phraya\", which means the \"army of the Phraya\". This later became Pattaya, the name of the wind blowing from the south-west to the north-east at the beginning of the rainy season.\n\nPattaya was a fishing village until the 1960s. Tourism began during the [[Vietnam War]], when American servicemen began arriving on [[R&R (military)|R&R]] (rest and relaxation). One large group who arrived from a base in [[Nakhon Ratchasima|Korat]] on 29 June 1959 and rented houses from Phraya Sunthorn at the south end of the beach, on what is now known as the \"Strip\", are credited with recommending Pattaya, whose fame spread by [[word of mouth]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schauseil|first1=Jan|title=Sattahip and the history of GIs coming to Pattaya|url=http://www.1stoppattaya.com/articles/sattahip_gis/|website=One Stop Pattaya|accessdate=12 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724115246/http://www.1stoppattaya.com/articles/sattahip_gis/|archive-date=24 July 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://thailand.sawadee.com/pattaya/introduction.html |title=Welcome to Pattaya |website=Sawadee.com |date=2018 |accessdate=25 February 2020 }}</ref>\n\n== Climate ==\nPattaya has a [[tropical wet and dry climate]], which is divided into the following seasons: hot and dry (December to February), hot and humid (March and April), and ''hot and rainy'' (May to November).\n\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n| collapsed    = Yes\n| location     = Pattaya (1981\u20132010)\n| metric first = Yes\n| single line  = Yes\n|Jan record hi